    "John Trapp": "And his second, Chileab, ] alias Daniel. { #1Ch 3:1 } By his name he should be lik e his father: he died early. \u2018\u039f\u03bd \u03c6\u03b9\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9 \u0398\u03b5\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b8\u03bd\u03b7\u03c3\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03b9\u03b5\u03bf\u03c2 And the third, Absalom the son of Maacah. ] More like his mother. Partus fere seqitur ventrem. Ingenium atque indoles plerunque matrissat. His name signifieth, The father\u2019s peace: but he proved like the sea called Pacific, which is troublous above measure.\nVer.\n3. And his second, Chileab, ] alias Daniel. {#1Ch 3:1} By his name he should be like his father: he died early. \u2018\u039f\u03bd \u03c6\u03b9\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9 \u0398\u03b5\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b8\u03bd\u03b7\u03c3\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03b9\u03b5\u03bf\u03c2 And the third, Absalom the son of Maacah.] More like his mother. Partus fere seqitur ventrem. Ingenium atque indoles plerunque matrissat. His name signifieth, The father\u2019s peace: but he proved like the sea called Pacific, which is troublous above measure.\nVer.",
    "930072315325": "And the second, Chileab, of Abigail the wife of Nabal the\nCarmelite, etc.] That is: who had been the wife of Nabal. This son\u2019s name\n[v_1Ch_3_1] is called Daniel, (<130301>1 Chronicles 3:1); and was the first name he had, and\nwhich his father gave him, because as if he should say, \u201cGod hath judged\nme\u201d, and pleaded the cause of his reproach from Nabal, (<092539>1 Samuel\n25:39); but why he should be called Chileab is not easy to say; the name is\ncommonly thought to signify \u201clike unto his father\u201d, or \u201call father\u201d: had all\nthe features of his father, and was exceedingly like him; the Jews have a\nfabulous story concerning this f49, not worth relating:\nand the third, Absalom the son of Maacah, the daughter of Talmai king of\n[v_1Sa_27_8] Geshur; in (<092708>1 Samuel 27:8) we read of David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s invading the land of the\nGeshurites; and the Jews say f50 that he then took the daughter of this king\ncaptive, and she being a beautiful woman married her, after made a\n[v_Deu_21_10] [v_Deu_21_11] [v_Deu_21_12] [v_Deu_21_13] [v_Deu_21_14] [v_Deu_21_15] [v_Deu_21_16] [v_Deu_21_17] [v_Deu_21_18] [v_Deu_21_19] [v_Deu_21_20] [v_Deu_21_21] [v_Deu_21_22] [v_Deu_21_23] proselyte according to the law in (<052110>Deuteronomy 21:10-23); but it\nshould be observed that David `[char_David_Rut_4]` slew all the women of that country, and left\nnot any alive; and besides that lay to the south of Judah, whereas this\nGeshur, of which Talmai was king, was a part of Syria, (<101508>2 Samuel\n15:8); and lay to the north of the land of Israel; and with this king David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\nhereby entered into an alliance, to strengthen his interest against Ishbosheth\nin those parts; of the trouble he met with from Absalom, (see <101301>2 Samuel\n13:1-18:33), etc. contrary to the expectations he had raised when he gave\n[v_1Ch_3_2] him the name of Absalom, or Leabsalom, as in (<130302>1 Chronicles 3:2); that\nis, one given \u201cfor his father\u2019s peace\u201d.\n31\nVer."
