  "5": {
    "John H. Walton, John K. Riches": "See Polzin, Samuel and the Deuteronomist, 24. would be \u2019lhym, similar to\n\u201cfor themselves\u201d (lhm). How\n5. Dawn, A Royal \u201cWaste\u201d of Time, 152\u201353.",
    "John Trapp": "Eglah David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s wife. ] His wife by a specialty: most dearly beloved. { a } Some make her to be Michel, and her son to be Nathan: but that is not very likely. { a } Praecipua et prima, ac prae aliis dilecta. -Lap.\nVer.\n5. Eglah David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s wife.] His wife by a specialty: most dearly beloved. {a} Some make her to be Michel, and her son to be Nathan: but that is not very likely. {a} Praecipua et prima, ac prae aliis dilecta. -Lap.\nVer.",
    "930072315325": "And the sixth, Ithream, by Eglah David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s wife, etc.] Who also is\nnot spoken of in any other place; only, in a like chronological account as\nthe former, it is remarked that the mother of this only is called David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s\nwife; the reason of which is supposed to be, either because she was a\nperson of no note, and had nothing else to distinguish her; but the same\nmay be said of the two foregoing; or because she was his beloved wife, his\nheifer, as her name signifies; hence the Jews f51 take her to be Michal his\nfirst wife, whom he greatly loved, and who, though she had no children\nafter her contempt of David `[char_David_Rut_4]` for playing before the ark, unto the day of her\ndeath, yet might have before: but it should be observed, that as yet she was\nnot returned to David `[char_David_Rut_4]` in Hebron; and when she was returned, did not seem\nto continue there long enough to have a son there; and besides, being his\nfirst wife, would not be reckoned last; but still more foreign is another\nnotion of the Jews f52, that she was Saul\u2019s widow, who though she might\nnot be married to another might be married to a king, as David `[char_David_Rut_4]` was; and\n[v_2Sa_12_8] this they suppose receives some confirmation from (<101208>2 Samuel 12:8); but\nafter all it may be this phrase \u201cDavid `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s wife\u201d, as some have observed, by a\nfigure the rhetoricians call \u201czeugma\u201d, or \u201chypozeugma\u201d, is to be joined to\n[v_2Sa_3_2] [v_2Sa_3_3] [v_2Sa_3_4] [v_2Sa_3_5] everyone of the women before mentioned, (<100302>2 Samuel 3:2-5), who were\nhis wives, and so called to distinguish them from his concubines, by whom\nhe had sons also. Polygamy, or plurality of wives, which David `[char_David_Rut_4]` gave into,\nis no favourable part of his character.\nVer."
  },
  "7": {
    "John H. Walton, John K. Riches": "This is the first time in the Hebrew Bible that the word the original reading\n\u201cGod\u201d to \u201cfor themselves\u201d in order to mashiah, \u201canointed [one],\u201d is used\nin a nominal manner avoid the impropriety of making \u201cGod\u201d the object\nof the to describe Israel\u2019s king. (The term is used as an adjectival\nverb. See McCarter, I Samuel, 96; Tsumura, The First Book modifier four times in\nLeviticus [4:3, 5, 16; 6:22] in the exof Samuel, 180; and Driver, Notes on\nthe Hebrew Text, 44. pression \u201cthe anointed priest.\u201d)",
    "John Trapp": "Wherefore hast thou gone in, &amp;c. ] Whether this charge were true or false, it appeareth not. But Ishbosheth, belike, suspected that Abner aspired to the kingdom. Compare #1Ki 2:17 2Sa 16:21 .\nVer.\n7. Ver.\n7. Wherefore hast thou gone in, &c.] Whether this charge were true or false, it appeareth not. But Ishbosheth, belike, suspected that Abner aspired to the kingdom. Compare #1Ki 2:17 2Sa 16:\n7. Ver.",
    "930072315325": "And Saul had a concubine, whose name [was] Rizpah, the\n[v_2Sa_21_8] daughter of Aiah, etc.] By whom he had two sons, (<102108>2 Samuel 21:8).\nJosephus f53 calls her father\u2019s name Sibathus:\n32\nand [Ishbosheth] said to Abner; though the word \u201cIshbosheth\u201d is not in\nthe text, it is rightly supplied; for no other can be supposed to speak:\nwherefore hast thou gone in unto my father\u2019s concubine? and defiled her;\nthough perhaps it was not so much the act of uncleanness that so much\noffended him, or the dishonour reflected on him and his family thereby, as\nit discovered an ambitious view in Abner to get the kingdom into his own\n[v_1Ki_2_22] hands, to which this was the leading step; (see <110222>1 Kings 2:22). Whether\nAbner was really guilty of this sin or no is not easy to determine; though,\nby his not absolutely denying it, it looks as if it was not merely a jealousy\nof Ishbosheth, or a false report made unto him; though, especially if he was\nnot fully satisfied of it, it would have been his wisdom to have said nothing\nof it to him, since his continuance on the throne so much depended on him.\nVer."
  },
  "1": {
    "John H. Walton, John K. Riches": "For numerous parallels, see Chisholm, \u201cStudy of",
    "John Trapp": "Now there was long war. ] Continuo iteratis proeliis: there was constant opposition, and continual skirmishing: so there is still betwixt Christ and Antichrist, betwixt the spirit and the flesh: and these will be bickering, whilst the world shall be standing. And the house of Saul waxed weaker and weaker. ] So do and shall do daily the eastern and western Antichrist. That stone cut out of the mountains without hands, shall bring down those golden images with a powder.\nVer.\n1. Now there was long war.] Continuo iteratis proeliis: there was constant opposition, and continual skirmishing: so there is still betwixt Christ and Antichrist, betwixt the spirit and the flesh: and these will be bickering, whilst the world shall be standing. And the house of Saul waxed weaker and weaker.] So do and shall do daily the eastern and western Antichrist. That stone cut out of the mountains without hands, shall bring down those golden images with a powder.\nVer.",
    "930072315325": "Now there was a long war between the house of Saul and the\nhouse of David `[char_David_Rut_4]`, etc.] The recent battle, though so much in favour of\nDavid `[char_David_Rut_4]`, did not, put an end to the war between him and Ishbosheth, which\nlasted five years longer; for it was when Ishbosheth had reigned two years\nthat that battle was fought, and he reigned five years longer; for not till his\ndeath, and when David `[char_David_Rut_4]` had reigned above seven years in Hebron, was he\nmade king over all Israel; and during this time peace was not made, but the\nwar carried on; though perhaps not in pitched battles, of which we no more\nread, but in skirmishes:\nbut David `[char_David_Rut_4]` waxed stronger and stronger; he having the advantage in all\nsuch skirmishes, and persons continually coming over to his side from the\nseveral tribes:\nand the house of Saul waxed weaker and weaker: being always worsted\nwhenever they skirmished with David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s men, and by continual revolts from\n30\nthem. This is reckoned an emblem of the kingdoms of Christ and antichrist,\nthe one increasing more and more, as it has and will do, and the other\ndecreasing, and before long will be consumed; and of the two parties in a\nregenerate man, grace and indwelling sin, the one as to its exercise growing\nstronger and stronger, and the other as to its influence on the outward\nconversation weaker and weaker.\nVer."
  },
